R Day

In RMarkdown files (*.rmd), you can add headers using the pound symbol (#). For example:

This is my header.

And a smaller header.

In R script files (.R), however, # serves to comment out R code that you do not want to execute. Similarly, if you embed your R code in your RMarkdown file, the # will work in the same way as it would in an R script file. See the example below.

# I don't want this code to run
# 4 + 4
8 + 8
## [1] 16

Check your working directory

getwd() # This should be Psyc109 on your desktop
## [1] "G:/Dropbox/Progs/_install/R/Exercises"

The following command installs the package on your computer. However, you can do this in RStudio as well. Just make sure to type the package names by paying attention to UPPERCASE and lowercase letters.

#install.packages("psych") # Warning, this will update the package.
#install.packages("moments")

The following command loads the package for use in the current script

library("psych")
## Warning: package 'psych' was built under R version 3.2.3
library("moments")

Read in a csv file

cdc <- read.csv("cdc.csv")
